<h2 class="call"><a name="device-status">Device status explained</a></h2>

<p>
Sometimes properties are not enough to describe the device status.
Think at a roller shutter for example. It has the property <code>status</code>
that accepts the values <code>open</code> and <code>close</code>. Now think at
what happens when a roller shutter is opening. It is neither open or close, but just
opening. To have a complete control over the device at every moment of its life use the
status resource.
</p>

<p>
Right now this service is not available on server side. This decision is due to performance
motivation and to the fact that the status information is a client visualization tasks.
A basic implementation is available on the
<a href="http://lelylan.github.com/devices-component-ng/">AngularJS Device Component</a>
where it is used to give a main description of the device status.
</p>

</article>

<article>

<h2 class="call"><a name="default-status-function">Default status function</a></h2>

<p>
Every status can set a default function. This means that when a device is in a specific
status we can associate a function and call it. For example when a <code>light is on</code>
the default function is <code>turn off</code> and when a <code>light is off</code> the default
function is <code>turn on</code>. See it in action in the <a href="http://try.lelylan.com">Lelylan Demo</a>.
</p>



</article>

<article>

<h2 class="call"><a name="accepted-values">Accepted values</a></h2>

<p>
The field <code>accepted</code> represents a list of key/label pairs where
<code>key</code> is the value used to update the <a href="/api/devices#update-properties">device properties</a>
and the <code>label</code> is a friendly description of the value.
Below you can see an example
where the values <code>on</code> and <code>off</code> are the values sent to the device
while <code>On</code> and <code>Off</code> are used as descriptions.
</p>

<div class="preview"><pre><code class="ruby"># list of accepted pair { "key": "label", "key": "label", ... }
"accepted": { "on": "On", "off": "Off" }</code></pre></div>

<br>

<p>
Populating the <code>accepted</code> list gives you two main benefits.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
  <strong>Uniformity</strong> - A clear definition of the values accepted form the device property.
  </li>
  <li>
  <strong>Presentation</strong> - Better user interface automatic generation.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
When creating a device, the <code>accepted</code> values are inherited by the
<a href="/api/types/properties">type properties</a>, but you can change it whenever
you want on your devices. This is useful in scenarios where a physical device needs to set
the accepted values (e.g. a television setting the channel names) for every specific device.
</p>

</article>
